msDesc.head: Missal, secular use of Linköping diocese

p.note: The paste-down is modern and glued on top of the original parchment paste-down, covering about two-thirds of it.

collation.p: Collation for quires 5, 11 and 12 is tentative. Parchment guards in all quires, a few of them from fragmented manuscripts. Quires 1 and 12 are mutilated and repaired. In quire 10 one bifolium is lost between and . Quire 11 is a quinion with one extra leaf and one bifolium. Between quires 12 and 13 an unknown number of quires is missing. After quire 14 several quires are missing.

p.note:
On the original parchment paste down is written in black ink in a late medieval hand: bekienner jak karl hanson hawa anamath aff skinberga ena klockio som vogh ett skeppund ok iv lispund oc v marker medh kleppen
. Top left corner: National Library modern book label with the current signum in black ink. Top centre in black ink by an 18-century hand: No. 58 Brocmanniana Missale Lincopense.
Late medieval and early modern pen trials in black ink by many hands.

binding.p: Late medieval binding. Dark brown leather over wooden boards. Four double raised bands and two endbands. Three clasps. On a modern leather label stamped in gold: Missale Lincopense M S C; and below: A 97.
binding.decoNote: , blind tooling filled in with red. Double lines creating a centre panel, which is divided by double lines horisontally, vertically and diagonally. Probably the same decoration on the .
binding.condition: Leather is heavily worn and and cracking along the spine. Leather is torn on the outer corners showing the boards and a large piece is missing on the . Decoration on is barely visible. Clasps are missing leaving only the brass nails or holes for the nails. A small piece of the wooden board is missing on the outer edge of the from where the middle clasp was fitted. Remains of a blue (silk?) ribbon glued to the and thread through a hole in the board to the .

history.origin:
Sweden , second half of the 15th century proposed in Lindberg (1923)
and supported by the watermarks. Helander (1957)
discusses dating based on the calendar and suggests between 1436–1441/8.
history.provenance:
The mention of Skönberga in the note on the , recovered by reagent in 1919, could suggest that the missal once belonged to the Church of Skönberga, Östergötland diocese, as proposed in Lindberg
: bekienner jak karl hanson hawa anamath aff skinberga ena klockio som vogh ett skeppund ok iv lispund oc v marker medh kleppen
. One Karl Hansson is recorded as a merchant in Söderköping who in sent a copper bell to Lübeck, see Källström (1939)
. Doubts regarding this provenance are raised in Kroon (1951)
.

The missal can also be connected with Västra Sten church, no longer standing, in Västra stenby socken, Linköping diocese, since Matthias Olavi Dingtunensis, a priest from Dingtuna in Västmanland (d. ), who officiated there in 1579-1608 has made an obit entry in the calendar for September 12, , , for his daughter, see Additions and Kroon (1951)
.

The name in the addition on , now almost completely obliterated but quoted in Lindberg (1923)
as Ex libris Bothvidi A nat. salvat. (1)624, could possibly refer to Bothvid Claudii Pallinaerus, son of the priest in Skönberga church Claudius Bothvidi (1599–1636), student at Uppsala University in , and district judge (häradshövding) in Bohuslän, see Linköpings stifts herdaminne, vol. 3
.

The missal belonged to Nils Reinhold Brocman (1731–1770), librarian at the Royal Library and antiquarian at the Antiquities Archive, see addition on : No. 58 Brocmanniana Missale Lincopense. Brocman bequeathed the manuscript to the Antiquities Archive , see transcription of his will from 1770 in U 89, where it is listed as Liturgica in Folio. Missale Lincopense Msct.
history.acquisition: From the Antiquities Archive to the Royal Library. Brocman's books are registered in the 19th-century inventory U 165:2: I Salongs soubassementerne. Skåpet 13 Brocmanniana.

note.p: The calendar is imperfect, the three first leaves missing, leaving only the months July-December. Particular feasts: Alexius (17 July), Anna (26 July), Transfiguration of Jesus (6 Aug.), Marcellus (4 Sep.), Dorotheus (9 Sep., shared with Gorgonius), Wenceslaus (28 Sep.), Cordula (22 Oct.). Local saints: St Birgitta (23 July, which is the date of her death, here recorded as the translatio), her canonisation and its octave (7 and 14 Oct.), St Botvid (28 July) and St Olof (29 July). An obit entry added 1575 on 12 September, see Additions.

watermark.term: Ox head with eyes and nostrils with single-line rod and star above, similar to Piccard II:2, VII, 385.

supportDesc.condition: The three extant leaves are what remains of an original ternion. The paper is brittle. Outer cornes are lost and edges are fraying. Burn marks on outer margin on are showing through to the rest of the leaves in the quire.

layout.note: Columns for the calendar are ruled in brown-black ink.

p.note: The names of the months and number of days have been added by a different hand.
For 12 September in the calendar: In Christe ex hac lacrimarum vallis emigressa est Filia mea Anna, quae in hac templo sepulta est hoc ipso die Anno domini 1575 Matthias Olaui Dingtunensis.

In the outer margin in black ink by a 16th-century hand is added a text in Swedish, partly lost due to wear of the paper, see Kroon (1951)
.

decoDesc.p: Text written in black and red ink.

msItem.title: Blessing and sprinkling of holy water
msItem.rubric: Sacerdos in dominicis diebus celebraturus in alba et stola paratus priusquam planetam seu casulam induat ... Sequitur exorzismus salis tonaliter dicendo Adiutorium Deinde conspergitur aqua cum Antiphona
msItem.note: The antiphon Asperges me is set to two different melodies depending on the degree of solemnity for the Sunday. It is followed by three collects.

msItem.title: Proper of time
msItem.rubric: Dominica prima in aduentum officium Dominica prima aduentus domini Officium
msItem.finalRubric: Explicit missale de tempore ab aduentu vsque in aduentum domini finitum

note.p: The temporal begins with Advent Sunday and ends with the Sunday before Advent Sunday. For every mass, the readings for Wednesday and Friday masses are appended at the end. The songs are fully notated. One bifolium is lost between and , which means that the end of the mass for the sixth Sunday after Trinity and the beginning of the seventh mass after Trinity are missing.
: guidelines and ruling but no text.

msItem.title: Dedication of the Church
msItem.explicit: dum iugiter per vestigia tua graditur ad celestia promissa te ducente peruenire mereatur Per

msItem.title: Ordo and Canon missae
msItem.rubric: Oracio ante altare cum genuflexione antequam induat vestes sacras
msItem.finalRubric: Et sic est finis laudetur deus in celis
msItem.note: This part begins with the priest's prayers before Mass and for dressing and it ends with prayers to be said after Mass. The prefaces are set to music. The canon is at with only a 2-line initial and no Crucifixion image.

msItem.title: Proper of saints
msItem.rubric: --- deficit queretur in communi de sanctis In vigilia sancti Andree Officium
msItem.explicit: complenda perceptis domine sacris supplices te rogamus ut intercedentibus
msItem.note: The proper of saints begins with the vigil for Saint Andrew (29 November). The feast of the Purification (2 February) ends imperfectly on and all subsequent feasts until the feast of Saint John the Baptist (24 June) on are missing, on account of one or more quires missing. The proper ends imperfectly with the feast for Saints Simon and Jude (28 October) on account of missing quires. Swedish saints: Knut (10 July), ; Birgitta (27 July), ; Botvid (28 july), ; Olaf (29 July),, Elin of Skövde (31 July), ; translation of Eskil (6 Oct.; rubric only), ; Birgitta (7 Oct.; rubric only), .

collation.signatures: Alphanumeric bifolium signatures mostly in red ink some in black, missing because of wear, trimming and repair.
collation.catchwords: Present on , an added leaf: omnes (not visible in the digitized image), and on 107v, (probably due to contemporary repair and resewing of the following quire): christus.

supportDesc.condition:
Paper is worn, edges brittle, upper corner missing on most leaves. Most leaves stained and affected by moisture. Contemporary and modern repairs are visible throughout, e.g.
. A hole from a burn has been repaired on . A piece is missing from top of page on resulting in some text loss. One bifolium is lost between and an unknown number of quires are missing between . After several leaves have been cut out, leaving the proper of saints incomplete.

layout.note: Columns and every other or third line are ruled in black ink.

handDesc.handNote: Gothic cursiva libraria/formata with occasional loopless ascenders.
Hybrida with occasional loops on ascenders.

p.note:
In the upper margin in black ink by a 17th-century hand: Ex libris Bothvidi A nat. salvat (1)624
. Now only partially preserved but quoted in Lindberg (1923)
.

Marginal corrections in black and red ink throughout, in both contemporary and early modern hands, sometimes also with musical notation, e.g.
.
In lower margin in red ink: a red cross drawn in a circle next to a short addition to the text.
In the lower margin in black ink by an early modern hand: johannes baptista officium misse.

physDesc.musicNotation: Square notation over a four-line staff.

decoDesc.p: Written in black ink with red for rubrics and initials.
decoDesc.decoNote: Plain initials in red and black over 1-2 lines, hanging I in red over 3-6 lines. For notated texts red and black initials, sometimes with interior reserved shapes, over the entire staff, e.g. . These are not always written in but space is reserved and guide letter present, e.g. . : Red initial C over 6 lines with interior reserved shapes. In the counterspace a green decoration with interior reserved shapes and red dots.
